al environment in which the issue is played out. Designer Animals uses non-technical language to explore the science behind animal biotechnology and the ethical frameworks at play in its surrounding debates. By investigating the interests of major stakeholders, including researchers on the cutting edge of science; mainstream and 'alternative' agriculture organizations; the animal welfare movement; and health care providers, patients, and researchers, the contributors illuminate the most important points of agreement and disagreement on this hotly contested topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal biotechnologyxEconomic aspects. 0aAnimal biotechnologyxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aAnimal biotechnologyxSocial aspects. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aSCIENCE / Biotechnology.2bisacsh1 aBrunk, Conrad G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunk, Conrad, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGjerris, Mickey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartley, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartley, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLétourneau, Lyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillips, Peter W.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRies, Nola M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRodgers, Leslie C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheremeta, Lorraine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, Paul B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266263640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442662636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com